## Foundational Principle

CTI is built on an explicit epistemological limit:

> *"CTI measures operationally verifiable cognitive transformations, not metaphysical truth."*

CTI does **not** attempt to prove consciousness, define absolute intelligence, or claim to understand subjective experience.

CTI only attempts to measure observable cognitive behavior within operational systems.

---

## First Law of CTI — The Cognitive Throughput Axiom

The operational capacity of an intelligent system can be measured by the rate at which it produces validated decisions over time.

$$I_t = \frac{\Delta D}{\Delta T}$$

| Variable | Definition |
|---|---|
| $I_t$ | Inference Throughput |
| $\Delta D$ | Validated Strategic Decisions |
| $\Delta T$ | Temporal Latency |

The First Law redefines cognition as measurable throughput. Under CTI, intelligence is not evaluated solely by outputs, but by the **rate of validated cognition**.

---

## Second Law of CTI — The Cognitive Efficiency Principle

Optimal cognition is not that which produces the most outputs, but that which generates **high-quality decisions under limited constraints**.

$$E_c = \frac{Q}{C \cdot T}$$

| Variable | Definition |
|---|---|
| $E_c$ | Cognitive Efficiency |
| $Q$ | Decision Quality |
| $C$ | Computational Cost |
| $T$ | Temporal Latency |

The Second Law establishes that higher-quality decisions increase efficiency, while excessive latency or resource consumption reduce it. Optimal cognition means **maximizing cognitive utility under real constraints** — not maximizing output volume.

---

## Formal Model of Cognitive Decision

CTI proposes that a valid decision can be formally modeled as a contextual optimization problem under limited constraints.

A valid decision is defined as:

> *"A state-transition operator that maximizes expected contextual utility under limited constraints of information and compute."*

$$\underset{D}{\arg\max} \; \mathbb{E}[U(D) \mid I, C, R]$$

Subject to:

$$R_c < R_{max}$$

| Variable | Meaning |
|---|---|
| $U(D)$ | Expected contextual utility |
| $I$ | Available information |
| $C$ | Operational context |
| $R$ | Resource constraints |
| $R_c$ | Computational cost |

Under CTI, a decision is not evaluated solely by its output — but by its capacity to **maximize operational utility** within real limits of time, information, and compute.

This implies optimal cognition is **not** perfect — it is **adaptively efficient under limited constraints**.

---

## Operational Definition of a Valid Decision

CTI defines a valid decision as:

> *"A cognitive output whose causal effect advances a defined objective within an observable operational context."*

This definition intentionally avoids metaphysical claims, requirements of absolute truth, and domain-specific semantics. It focuses on:

- **Causal effectiveness**
- **Operational observability**
- **Contextual utility**

---

## Philosophical Boundary

CTI explicitly rejects claims about consciousness, phenomenology, metaphysical intelligence, or absolute truth. CTI only evaluates observable operational cognition, measurable decision transformations, and reasoning systems under constraints.

| Problem | CTI Scope |
|---|---|
| Cognitive throughput | ✅ |
| Decision efficiency | ✅ |
| Operational validation | ✅ |
| Cognitive observability | ✅ |
| Consciousness | ❌ |
| Subjective experience | ❌ |
| Absolute truth | ❌ |

